Change log:
	Unfortunately I was not especially diligent in updating this log.
	This is a combination of logs from more than one place.


20220213 handler
	Started coding the single SYS entry point version.

20220218 handler
	Fleshed it all out.  Just exactly fits without any tricks.

20220330 handler
	Moved some variables to the data break locations and now have
	four words free.

20220427 handler
	Added the 20220330 comment.  Added the boot code which isn"t really
	used but is what ends up in memory.  Made changes in the boot code
	after revisiting the boot process.  Moved BOOT2 such that it starts
	at 0037 and ends at 0046 which is the last location the traditional
	style OS/8 boots use in the boot sector.

20220428 handler
	Decided to make the boot more like all the other handlers.  The
	boot process consists of starting the BOOT1 code, telling the
	server to go into boot mode where it sends the help version of
	BOOT2 and then sends the boot block.  BOOT2 reads the boot block
	at 0 and then moved the pieces into their locations and then
	JMPS TO 7605 to start OS/8.

20220501 handler
	Added a reloc just before the $ at the end for symmetry.

20220503 handler
	Fixed a comment and added back in the nops after the isz which should
	get skipped only when transfering the last word of a field.

20220507 Handler
	Commented out the correct device header and changed it to match
	the RK8E.  This is so we should be able to copy in this header
	onto a working RK05 disk image for an initial boot.

20220526 Server
	Investigated the boot block to see what gets loaded at 07600
	through 07606 which is:
	07600	4207	JMS 7607	/ CALL THE SYS HANDLER
	07601	5000	05000		/ WRITE 010 BLOCKS FROM FIELD 0
	07602	0000	0000		/ STARTING AT 0000
	07603	0033	0033		/ TO BLOCK 0033
	07604	7602	CLA HLT		/ IF THERE IS AN ERROR
	07605	6213	CDF CIF 10	/ FAR JMP TO FIELD 1
	07606	5267	JMP 7667	/ COULD BE VERSION DEPENDENT
	I suspect that the above might be the same on all OS/8 versions.
	The JMP at 7606 is the only thing that might change, the rest
	are kind of locked in concrete.  Should put a warning in the
	server if these are not correct.

20220527 Both
	Moved the handler code to the rasp pi and placed in a subdir
	called handler.  Renamed the server subdir to server.  Added
	this Readme.  Installed palbart on the pi as well.

20220530 Server
	Verified the hand toggled code loads the help loader which then
	loads the boot sector over itself.

20220703 tsttty
	I am a little confused about using the tty device as the
	console so I did some testing in this subdir.  The plan is
	to open /dev/tty with a new descriptor and leave STDIN_FILENO,
	STDOUT_FILENO, and STDERR_FILENO alone.  Tested the output.

20220704 tsttty
	Continued testing with the input from the keyboard portion.
	And it seems to all work as well.

20220705 server
	Changed the code to use the stuff I learned from tsttty.
	Put the loopback program in the 8:
	6031 KSF
	5200 JMP 200
	6036 KRB
	6046 TLS
	5200 JMP 200
	And while this does not test every code it does echo what I type
	just as expected.  It does seem to be in raw mode both directions.
	Found a bug involving precidence.  if( pdp_ch&0370 == 020 ) fails
	because == has a higher precidence than &.

20220706 server
	Verified that the fix from yesterday worked.  Started debugging
	the next problem which is that the address of the handler caller
	is not being received correctly.  I am seeing a 5223 instead of
	a 7671.

20220707 handler
	Found a bug in get12 where if the link was set then the value
	would have 010 added to it.  Also cleared the link in send12
	although i don't think it would matter there.

20220707 server
	Trying to figure out why it is not getting the correct address of
	the Caller.

20220707 recvtst
	Wrote a program to receive and test characters sent by the 8.  A
	simple counting sequence was used and a "." was printed every
	256 characters.  This was to verify that Linux on the Pi could
	accept characters at full rate (9600 baud at least.)

20220708 handler
	Changed the names of the read and write routines to match their
	functions relative to the server since it is the one giving the
	orders.

20220718 handler
	Moved some code around so setup is at the second handler entry
	point.  If the server does not see 7611 (7607+2) as the initial
	called address, it knows the second entry point was called.

20220719 server
	Found the bug that was causing the 8 to jump off into the weeds.
	It was a 62X3 instead of a 062X3.  The handler far jmp was
	executing a JMS 0105 instead of the CDF CIF and returning to the
	caller.

20220720 handler
	Moved the WKUP constant into the NOP position after an ISZ to
	save a word.  The WKUP character will execute as a harmless
	AND instruction.  This gave enough space to make the second
	RK05 entry point functional so that code was added as well.

20220720 server
	Added the functionality of the second device for the RK05.
	Added the code to write out the system image when the F1
	key is pressed to exit.  Added the code to detect operations off
	the end of the medial.  Started removing superfluous debug
	stuff.

20220721 Documentation
	Time to get this ready for some sort of release.

20220725 server
	I had previously added in the detection for access off the end
	of the media.  Added in the error return to OS/8 for this
	action.  Continued the cleanup of the debugging messages.  Added
	comments for places that need work in csd.c like control C
	testing.  Added a version number display for when the server
	starts up.  If it knows about the installed handler then it
	silently starts up.

20220725 Documentation
	Decided to suggest not messing with the BDTIME constant in the
	handler.  The default value should work on anything that doesn't
	run slower than 9600 baud.

20220725 0.1 Beta
	as soon as I close this out I am going to make a tarball for
	Kyle and Vince and email it off.

20220726 Server
	Found PDP_SP and PDP_BAUD were also defined in tty.c so those
	are now only in csd.c.  Added the conversion of teh DEL key
	to a RUBOUT (0177) code in tty.c

20220727 Server
	Added a usage message if an unknown command line option is
	specified.  Added code to help detect a bad image by verifying
	the even and odd bytes are within range before assembly into
	a 12 bit word.  If someone had an endian issue this could be
	a problem.

20220727 handler
	The TSF flag was being set to the wrong state on return.  This
	was the cause of R PIP hanging the machine.  It is not clear
	why running R PAL8 and then R PIP didn't have an issue but
	correcting the TSF flag resolved it.

20220728 0.20 Beta
	Tarball for Vince and Kyle.

20220802 Documentation
	Forgot to add an entry for this.  Started reorganizing the
	documentation into the outer consd directory.  Consolidated the
	changelogs into this one file.

20220802 Handler
	copied CONSYS.PA to PCHSYS.PA and then corrected CONSYS.PA to
	make it a handler independent from the RK05.  This is necessary
	because handlers cannot share an entry point address.  What this
	means is that since RKB0 has its entry point at page offset 0021.
	The CONSYS.PA has CDB0 entry point at page offset 0041 so that it
	can be used with Kyle's Serial Disk if desired.

20220808 Handler
	Added CONNON.PA which is the non system handler supporting CSD0
	through CSD7 on entry points 40-47.  Also RKA0 and RKB0 on entry
	points 20 and 21, and finally DTA0 on entry point 10.

20220812 Server
	Started making changes to add more block devices.  Added the CSD
	devices and changed the earlier configuration to make it RK05.
	Stubbed in the DECtape.

20220823 Server
	Added support for CSD0-7 devices.  Keeping the boot with an RK05
	image so these are currently supported only on the nonsys
	handler.

20220830 Server
	Dropped back to just CSD0-3 for supported devices.  Having eight
	devices takes up too much space to be necessary.  Started
	modifying csd.c to handle multiple devices selected by the entry
	point address.  Still only supports RK05 as the system image.

20220831 Server
	Fixed a bug in yesterday's changes and tested on Vince's 8/a.
	changed tty.c to allow for a cygwin difference but this only
	partially corrected the problem.  The change allows a -1 return
	from read to indicate no characters were present.  Cygwin does
	not turn off echo correctly (at least on this ancient version
	running under Vista.  Decided to not worry about Cygwin for now.

20220831 Documentation
	Verified the 9600 baud value of BDTIME on the 8/a.

